Hepatic abscess caused by Salmonella typhi: diagnosis and management by percutaneous echo-guided needle aspiration. Three cases of liver abscesses due to Salmonella typhi (2 solitary, 1 with double localization in the right lobe) are described in which specific diagnosis was based on percutaneous echo-guided aspiration of the lesions. Haemocultures and coprocultures were negative, in all cases, and pus-cultures of aspirated material from cavities grew Salmonella typhi Widal became significantly positive only in one patient 15 days after discharge. Percutaneous needle drainage, combined with chloramphenicol therapy, was successfully performed under echo guidance